She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you reading memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's just a few days away."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out because she was "an error" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in a family otherwise composed solely of boys.
Ivory was also like that, in her own way. When she had declared herself non-binary, it felt as though the world had changed too. They had assigned her tasks that condemned her to solitude as punishment for her difference.
Iel also had to remain in service to the princess, but that wasn't much of an issue since it made her an ally.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?" Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming up soon. Kari nodded, a sad glimmer in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As she asked the question, Iel remembered what Kari had said last time.
No, Kari replied with a touch. Ivory knew it was a difficult topic for her. It was the day she was confined to her room and her mother was banished. When it happened, Iel was just a baby, but she remembered the servants' and citizens' outrage. She had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you feel like doing?" Iel asked. Kari's eyes lit up with enthusiasm. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when Iel looked at it...
15 cm x 15 cm painting
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" asked Ivory, turning towards the silent princess who was frantically tapping, shaking her pigtails back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly, seeing the usually reserved princess get passionate about something. This was the first time she had asked for something not related to books and not found in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" offered Ivory, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and wrapped herself back in her thick blanket, lost in memories.
Iel left the room relieved. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking about topics outside her usual interests, such as painting.
Iel navigated the castle corridors, trying to ignore the servants' whispers.
"I heard she is possessed by Queen Eirwen, which is why she always goes into that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered their ears, as trying to ignore it didn't work. Iel headed towards the royal painter's room, which was in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, as worked on as the one Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primal dragons, according to legend, who had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved history.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a chaotic scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered throughout the room, easels covering every last inch of wall. Surprisingly, Iel saw none of that. The room was clean, with a red velvet background and a stool just in front. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, having his portrait done.
"Hello, Ivory! Are you here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" asked Aquilo to Ivory, winking at her.
"Pardon, little prince," he replied, ignoring him partially to look for the objects his silent friend wished for. "I'm just here to get supplies."
"Oh, the girl will be leaving very soon, won't she?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box that he had scavenged. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought about that. "Oh my dear, you know it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!" he murmured.
"I have to go," he said suddenly uncomfortable, because of the prince's words, which reminded him of all the bad things people said about his gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Are you leaving already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" he scolded.
"No one will know. Others won't believe it, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to live." He turned back to the painter for a moment, then leaned towards Ivory. "What do you think about a romantic meeting?" Iel shivered. Indeed, Iel had received many threats before, but never from a prince, let alone the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word no means?" Iel said, pushing the prince out of his way.
"Nope," replied Aquilo with a smile. Naturally, a prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why want a romantic meeting with me instead of others? You must have a hundred or so suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling: "500, to be exact." He threw back his hair, making it fly in the cold air.
"So, why me instead of another? I am the threat to the palace." Iel wrapped his arms around himself.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
